    <article class="mustdos-article">
      <p class="back-link"><a href={`${base}research-questions/`}>← Research</a></p>
      <h1 id="intro">10 must do&rsquo;s</h1>
      <p class="mustdos-lead">
        Research within economics and business sciences often begins when someone asks a specific question that has no
        obvious answer. Such questions need further analysis to pinpoint their exact nature and scope. Often questions
        are merely <strong>phrased</strong> poorly and ambiguously, and with some rephrasing can be answered easily. Other
        questions may be stated clearly but have no clear, direct answer, and should be investigated further.
      </p>
      <p class="mustdos-lead">
        In this reading, &ldquo;must do&rdquo; aspects for conceptualising a research question are discussed. In
        reality the process is rarely linear: you may need to revisit earlier steps as clarity grows. When that
        happens, it is usually a good sign that the question is becoming more focused.
      </p>

      <section id="must-do-1" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #1: Find a personal itch</h2>
        <p>
          While reviewing topic options, find at least one thing that makes you itch to do research on it—something
          worth knowing more about. You need a problem or issue you <strong>care about</strong>. Problems researchers
          care about tend to be more focused, stir emotion, and the work is more likely to make a real difference.
        </p>
        <p>
          In undergraduate study you often work on what others deem important. In postgraduate research you can choose
          what <em>you</em> think matters. Are there problems in a discipline that have always interested you? Issues that
          make you angry or excited? Good research is seldom emotionless; people often do their best work on topics that
          stir strong feelings. Notice which issues pull you in during lectures, or what you keep talking and reading
          about.
        </p>
        <p>
          It is important to find something you care about before moving on. Research is hard, and you need a pull that
          gets you through difficult stretches. Caring about the problem helps a great deal.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-2" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #2: Make others care</h2>
        <p>
          Research is done in the hope that it can make a positive difference in the real world. That means writing for
          other people: if they do not read it, the work changes nothing. You must get others to care about the itch you
          identified. If you cannot, you risk the biggest insult a researcher can hear: <strong>&ldquo;So what?&rdquo;</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          The best way to make others care is to create a <strong>problem</strong> for them. The word comes from the
          Greek <em>problema</em>, meaning an obstacle to action. In most disciplines a problem is tied to the real
          world: you must act when there is a <strong>gap</strong> between where you are and where you want to be, as in
          the diagram below. Where you are can be bad or merely &ldquo;good enough&rdquo;; where you want to be should
          be better.
        </p>

        <figure class="mustdos-figure">
          <img src={imgGap} alt="Diagram: Bad or OK current state labelled Where we are, desired Better state labelled Where we want to be, with a vertical arrow and GAP between them." loading="lazy" />
          <figcaption>Gap between current situation and desired goal.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The bigger the gap, the bigger the problem. Closing the gap requires <strong>action</strong>; if that action is
          hard, you have a problem—for example wanting to pass a course when you have only just started and success looks
          difficult.
        </p>
        <p>
          What makes it difficult is that real-world <strong>obstacles</strong> block action and keep the gap open, as in
          the next figure. Obstacles might include lack of funding, wrong incentives, poor time management, and many
          others. Because we deal with people and things in the real world, highlight obstacles that are genuinely
          real-world.
        </p>

        <figure class="mustdos-figure">
          <img
            src={imgObstacles}
            alt="Diagram: same Where we are and Where we want to be bars; the gap contains blue circles as obstacles and an orange zigzag path through them to the goal."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>Obstacles in the gap make closing it harder.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          In South Africa, mothers below a certain income can receive a government grant per child. That policy creates
          several problems: the grant may be too small, or it may create incentives for some young women to become
          pregnant for income. Framed as a gap: we want the grant to reduce poverty, but the current situation may be
          that the grant keeps people in poverty. Why not close the gap? Because real-world obstacles stand in the
          way—for example the social and political disruption that could follow from redesigning the system.
        </p>

        <h3 id="audience">i) Identify your audience</h3>
        <p>
          A problem is always a problem <em>for someone</em>. You need a group in mind when you build the problem. Show
          that your itch is their problem too; that focus sharpens your writing. Like a text message or a report, research
          should be written with someone in mind—otherwise it drifts.
        </p>
        <p>
          Think carefully <em>for whom</em> you are creating the problem. To make a difference you must convince people
          with both the <strong>power</strong> and the <strong>interest</strong> to act. Many groups may care; often only
          one has real power. That is the group you should write for—the <strong>high power, high interest</strong>
          quadrant in the diagram below.
        </p>

        <figure class="mustdos-figure mustdos-figure--wide">
          <img
            src={imgStakeholders}
            alt="Stakeholder matrix: four quadrants for combinations of high and low power and interest."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>Power and interest: prioritise high power and high interest when you need action.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          In the grant example, many groups are affected: government, taxpayers, parents, children, social workers, and
          more. Taxpayers, parents, and social workers may have high interest but little power to remove obstacles;
          children may sit in the low power, low interest quadrant. If the problem is in the <em>design</em> of the grant,
          the department responsible for that design has the greatest power—so you write with government in mind. That
          does not erase other stakeholders: convincing government can improve life for everyone else. You cannot write
          equally to all audiences; social workers and ministers need different framing.
        </p>
        <p>
          In short: list who cares, then choose the group with the greatest power to address the issue. Next, frame the
          problem for them so they care enough to act.
        </p>

        <h3 id="explain-problem">ii) Explain the nature of the real-world problem</h3>
        <p>
          For that audience, explain what they want in the real world versus what they have now. Use facts from
          scientific sources and credible data to show the gap is large.
        </p>
        <p>
          Explain why the problem is hard to solve: what are the main obstacles, and how do they block action? For
          example, South Africa wants less poverty but also wants to limit abuse of assistance. Removing the grant would
          stop one kind of abuse but worsen poverty; keeping it may create dependency. That dilemma is an obstacle that
          forces a rethink of grant design—especially when funding to continue the programme in its current form is
          tight.
        </p>

        <h3 id="support-claim">iii) Support the claim</h3>
        <p>
          Use scientific sources and credible data to support every claim about the problem. Without evidence, it is
          hard to convince a busy audience that your problem deserves attention among many competing demands.
        </p>
        <p>
          After you have described the problem, plan how you will introduce it in context for that audience. Must do #3
          turns to how you <strong>provide that context</strong> before you state the problem in full.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-3" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #3: Provide the context</h2>
        <p>
          When you communicate the problem, not everyone will agree that it matters—or even that it exists. If readers
          disagree with you early on, it becomes much harder to win them over. That is a key reason to provide
          <strong>context</strong> first.
        </p>
        <p>
          Context gives the broad background or the story that led to the problem. Usually there is little in it that
          readers can disagree with, because you have not yet explained the problem as such. It builds common ground,
          and from there you can lead them toward the problem. There are two main techniques; aim for one or two
          paragraphs at most.
        </p>

        <h3 id="context-narrative">i) Narrative</h3>
        <p>
          Relate the chain of events from just before the problem emerged to the moment it became visible. Speed
          matters—do not lose the reader in a long history lesson.
        </p>
        <p>
          Continuing the grant example: you might start with the period just before the policy, when poverty was at
          severe levels, especially among women and children. In 1994 the government changed; the new administration
          considered many options. One was a small grant per child for poor mothers. Then reports began to emerge of
          teenagers becoming pregnant in order to qualify for the grant. When you tell this story, anchor it in data and
          facts from credible sources so it is hard to dispute, and move step by step toward the problem you want taken
          seriously, as in the diagram below.
        </p>

        <figure class="mustdos-figure mustdos-figure--flow">
          <img
            src={imgNarrativeFlow}
            alt="Three horizontal orange arrows in sequence: high poverty among women, new government considers grants, then disturbing reports emerge."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>Narrative chain: from background through policy to the emergence of the problem.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Narrative is often the easiest and most persuasive way to set context, because it rests on historical facts
          and because people tend to be less critical when they follow a story. It works best when there was a clear
          &ldquo;before&rdquo; and &ldquo;after.&rdquo; If the problem has always existed, use the next technique instead.
        </p>

        <h3 id="context-pyramid">ii) Inverted pyramid</h3>
        <p>
          Start very broad and narrow step by step until you reach the specific problem—like an upside-down pyramid,
          from general to particular, as in the diagram below. Again, keep it tight: long stretches of vague generality
          will lose the reader.
        </p>
        <p>
          The grant case fits this pattern too: begin with poverty as a worldwide issue, then show it is especially
          severe in South Africa; note that governments consider various tools against poverty, and that South Africa chose
          the child grant; then show that after implementation, a new problem appeared&hellip;
        </p>

        <figure class="mustdos-figure mustdos-figure--wide">
          <img
            src={imgInvertedPyramid}
            alt="Inverted blue pyramid divided into horizontal bands labelled Poverty worldwide, Poverty in SA, Solutions, Grants, and But… at the tip."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>Inverted pyramid: from broad topic to the specific tension (&ldquo;But…&rdquo;).</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Because you begin broadly, you build common ground: sweeping statements backed by data are harder to dispute.
          Both techniques help readers orient themselves and see where you are coming from. We do this in stories—we
          rarely open with the climax, but with &ldquo;once upon a time.&rdquo; We do it in film—often an establishing view
          of the city before the camera zooms to where the action is.
        </p>
        <p>
          Context also serves a psychological purpose: if readers agree with you at the start, they are more likely to
          agree later. The familiar (if grim) analogy is boiling a frog: you do not throw it into hot water or it will jump
          out. You put it in pleasantly cool water where it can swim; then you turn up the heat gradually so it does not
          notice and falls asleep as the water heats. The point for writing is to warm your audience to your view in stages—not through
          deception, but through a sequence of shared premises before you ask for the hard commitment.
        </p>
        <p>
          Salespeople use the same rhythm. A life-insurance salesperson will not open with &ldquo;Do you want to buy an
          education policy from me?&rdquo;—too easy to say no. Instead they ask a series of questions to which you will
          tend to say yes: &ldquo;Do you love your children?&rdquo; Yes. &ldquo;So you want the best for them?&rdquo;
          Yes. &ldquo;And to give them the best, is it important that they get a good university education?&rdquo;
          Yes&hellip; until &ldquo;Do you want to buy an education policy?&rdquo; is more likely to meet with
          &ldquo;Yes, of course.&rdquo; In the same way you are &ldquo;selling&rdquo; your research to readers so they will
          care: start with statements they can agree with, then lead them to the real-world problem.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-4" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #4: Briefly jot down the &lsquo;real-world&rsquo; problem</h2>
        <p>
          You are now ready to briefly write the &lsquo;real-world&rsquo; problem: the background to the research, in
          which you will put together steps 2 and 3. First, you will write down the context from step 3. The context
          leads to the real-world problem, so then you write down the explanation of the problem from step 2.
        </p>
        <p>
          This should not take more than one page, and of this one page you should spend more on explaining the actual
          problem in the real world, because it is this that convinces people that they should care.
        </p>
        <p>
          Look at the example below from an actual piece of writing by a student with some of the details deleted. The
          background starts with a broad discussion of an issue, moves to the discussion of the issue in South Africa
          and how it led to a particular law. Then it explains the problem with that specific law. Facts are used, and
          references back up all the important claims.
        </p>

        <div class="mustdos-example">
          <p class="mustdos-example-title">Background to the research</p>
          <p>
            The issue of ___ is one of vital importance for ___ given ___. The assumption here is that ___ (Brown &amp;
            Reilly, 2009). But according to Campbell et al. (2001) the ___, so it now takes more ___, and thus ___ has
            become ever so important (Ibbotson &amp; Kaplan, 2000).
          </p>
          <p>
            ___ plays a vital role in the ___ since the level of ___ depends on (Maginn et al., 2007). As a result, to
            protect the ___ from being exposed to ___, the South African government implemented the ___ Act of ___. All
            ___ in South Africa have to comply with ___ of the ___ Act, which sets a list of guidelines with the sole
            purpose of ___. What the regulation appears to ignore is that ___ can be ___ (Bodie, 1983; Gorton &amp;
            Rouwenhorst, 2006). There are two direct ways ___ (Maginn et al. 2007). Despite these benefits, ___ can
            therefore not take advantage of ___ due to the limitations imposed by the ___ Act. According to Bodie and
            Rosansky (1980) an ___ could have reduced ___ while ___.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          Initially you will focus on the real-world obstacles that make it difficult to solve the real-world problem.
          But there is another kind of obstacles that needs to exist to create the need for research, and we turn to
          this next.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-5" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #5: Find out why current studies are not good enough</h2>
        <p>
          Until now you have shown that there is a problem in the real-world that your audience should care about. You
          have identified real-world obstacles that make it difficult to do something about the problem (like lack of
          funding, wrong policies, corruption etc.).
        </p>
        <p>
          But if research is necessary, we have to show that research plays a role in solving the real-world problem.
          Real-world problems cannot be solved by research, because a piece of research cannot walk around and change
          the world. But it could be that the research is not good enough to help people solve the real-world problem,
          so that further research would give people the knowledge they need to address the real-world problem.
        </p>
        <p>
          So, in this step you have to move from the real world (the world of people and things) into the knowledge
          world (the world of ideas and studies). You have to show that another obstacle in the way of addressing the
          real-world problem is some lack of knowledge about it. In other words, you have to show that there is also a
          <strong>knowledge problem</strong> (or research problem).
        </p>
        <p>
          If we knew everything about the real-world problem, there would be no need for research. If previous research
          studied everything about the real world problem completely and perfectly, we would not need further research.
          So it is important to show that one of the reasons we cannot solve the problem is because we don&rsquo;t know
          enough. And how do we know if there is a lack of knowledge? We look at previous research studies about the
          real-world problem and find something that is either missing or confusing in previous studies.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a novice researcher the easiest way to find out where the knowledge about a problem is inadequate is to
          look for gaps in the existing studies, that is look for areas where there is little or no research. When you
          find a gap, you can do research to fill the gap, and so help to create knowledge that may help to solve the
          real-world problem. The main kind of gaps are:
        </p>

        <h3 id="gap-types">Kinds of gaps</h3>
        <ul class="mustdos-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Time gaps:</strong> you find previous studies about the real-world problem, but notice that the
            studies are outdated and are no longer relevant. New updated research is therefore needed based on the
            latest data.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Place gaps:</strong> you find previous studies, but notice that the studies are only applied to some
            places. New research is therefore needed that applies the relevant ideas to places (cities, industries,
            countries etc.) neglected by researchers in the past.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>People gaps:</strong> you find previous studies, but notice that the studies are only applied to some
            people or groups. New research is therefore needed that applies the relevant ideas to the groups neglected
            by researchers in the past.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Method gaps:</strong> you find previous studies, but notice that the studies use methods that are
            wrong, inappropriate or outdated. New research is therefore needed using the best available or new methods.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          It may be possible to find larger gaps&mdash;where a theory has never been tested before or an empirical
          phenomenon has never been researched before, but this is rare.
        </p>
        <p>
          You may also look for aspects of the real-world problem where previous studies disagree or where there such
          studies have not been able to solve a puzzle. When you find such confusion in previous studies you can make a
          contribution, but only if you have a way to do the research differently in order to settle the disagreement or
          solve the puzzle.
        </p>
        <p>
          I want to repeat that in this step we are no longer investigating the real world, we are investigating the
          studies about the real world. We are no longer looking for facts about the real-world problem, instead we are
          looking at the previous studies about the real-world problem to see where they are missing something.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some people, like J&ouml;rgen Sandberg and Mats Alvesson in their various writings on research, have pointed
          out that gap-spotting does not lead to interesting research. While I agree with them, simple gap-spotting is
          sufficient when you are still learning about research. Once you gain more confidence, you can try other
          approaches that involve challenging the assumptions of the discipline or generating new ideas. These
          approaches are discussed in a more advanced workshop.
        </p>
        <p>
          The challenge is to convince that, given all the research out there about your real-world problem, you have
          found something inadequate. Here are some ways to do that:
        </p>

        <h3 id="convince-inadequate">Convincing readers research is inadequate</h3>
        <ul class="mustdos-list">
          <li>
            If you found that there is confusion about an issue in the form of a <strong>disagreement</strong>, then:
            (1) you mention the studies (by referencing them) that take one view on the real-world problem; (2) mention
            the studies (by referencing them) that take the opposing view; (3) explain what it is they disagree on; and
            (4) explain what research is still needed to settle the disagreement (and this is the research you will do).
          </li>
          <li>
            If you found that there is confusion in the form of an <strong>unsolved puzzle</strong>, then: (1) you
            explain the puzzle with reference to studies that show that there is a puzzle; (2) mention the studies (by
            referencing them) that have attempted and failed to solve the puzzle; and (3) explain what research is still
            needed that might help to solve the puzzle (and this is the research you will do).
          </li>
          <li>
            If you found that there is a <strong>gap</strong> in the research it is more difficult. The best strategy
            is to group the existing studies, and systematically mention them so that it become obvious that there is an
            area where no studies exist. Suppose you spotted a combination of a place and method gap: that there are no
            good studies investigating whether government grants for children cause teenage pregnancies in rural areas.
            You would first identify that there are studies worldwide by mentioning the main studies in other countries.
            From there you would show that there are few South African studies, but most of them were conducted in
            cities, and that those in rural areas cannot be trusted because their samples were too small. From that you
            would conclude that it is not clear whether grants cause teenage pregnancies in rural areas in South
            Africa, and that we therefore need a study in rural areas that use a bigger sample. Every time you mention
            studies you need to provide the references to those studies even though you won&rsquo;t discuss the studies
            in detail.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <figure class="mustdos-figure mustdos-figure--wide">
          <img
            src={imgGapSpotting}
            alt="Four coloured puzzle pieces around a central question mark, numbered 1 to 4, narrowing from worldwide studies to rural South African studies with small samples."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>
            Systematic gap-spotting: from worldwide studies, to few in South Africa, to cities only, to unreliable
            rural samples&mdash;leading to the knowledge question in the centre.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Look at the following example based on finding a combination of a time gap, place gap and confusion about the
          problem:
        </p>

        <div id="knowledge-example" class="mustdos-example">
          <p>
            Literature on the impact of ___ has yielded inconsistent results across the globe. For example, in his
            US-based study, Stiroh (2004) finds that ___ Converse to this finding, and also based on US commercial
            banks, DeYoung and Rice (2004) find that&hellip; Another study by Williams and Rajaguru (2013), set in
            Australia not only finds that ___ but also that ___.
          </p>
          <p>
            In addition to the inconclusive findings, many of the studies (Smith, 2015; Zalamea, 2013) investigate the
            impact of ___ mainly in developed countries. However, the extent to which these findings can be generalised
            to developing economies is limited because ___. Although South African research exists, in the form of a
            study by Oberholzer and Van der Westhuizen (2009), the data examined covers a time period (2001 to 2008)
            which means it is outdated because ___.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>There are a couple of things I want you to notice from this extract:</p>
        <ul class="mustdos-list">
          <li>
            The author does not discuss the real-world problem or issues in the real world. The discussion is focused
            only on the studies: what has been done and what is inadequate about the research.
          </li>
          <li>
            There are lots of references. Every time the author mentions a study or makes a claim about the studies, he
            provided references. This means you cannot write about the knowledge problem until you have read the
            important literature about the real-world problem.
          </li>
          <li>
            The author does not discuss the studies, he simply mentions them so that we can see what has, and has not,
            been done. A more detailed discussion of the studies can be provided later in the literature review. At
            this point you should just give a rapid overview of the state of the research, so you will complete your
            explanation of the knowledge problem in less than half-page.
          </li>
          <li>
            The discussion is systematic. Studies are grouped and discussed in a logical order so that it leads to a
            conclusion of what exactly is inadequate in the research thus far. The author does not simply list the
            studies in some random order.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          By the time you have explained the knowledge problem, you should be able to conclude in a single sentence:
          &ldquo;So we (as researchers) therefore don&rsquo;t know&hellip;&rdquo; For example, if there are conflicting
          result on whether lower taxes lead to people spending more (let&rsquo;s say some studies say it leads to more
          spending, while other studies say taxes make no difference) we can conclude: we therefore do not know if lower
          taxes stimulate consumers to spend more. If, for example, we found a time gap (say the last study on taxes and
          consumer spending was done in 2006 in Colombia) we can conclude: we therefore do not know if lower taxes
          stimulated Colombian consumers to spend more after 2007.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you are interested, you can consult the <a href={`${base}research-questions/contribution/#types-of-contributions`}>types of contributions</a> guide for a quick overview of the many kinds of research
          contributions. This will also give you a sense of how easy it is to find a contribution that you can make.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-6" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #6: Derive the provisional research question</h2>
        <p>
          Once you can state what is inadequate about the research it is a simple matter to derive the provisional
          research question. You simply restate the statement in the form of a grammatical question, with a question
          mark at the end, as the next table shows.
        </p>

        <div class="mustdos-table-wrap">
          <table class="mustdos-table">
            <caption class="mustdos-table-caption">
              From knowledge problem to research question
            </caption>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th scope="col">Statement of knowledge problem</th>
                <th scope="col">Research question</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>We don&rsquo;t know what is 1+1.</td>
                <td>What is 1+1?</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>We don&rsquo;t know whether it will rain later.</td>
                <td>Will it rain later?</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>We don&rsquo;t know if the road is congested.</td>
                <td>Is the road congested?</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  We don&rsquo;t know if lower taxes stimulated Colombian consumers to spend after 2007.
                </td>
                <td>Did lower taxes stimulate Colombian consumers to spend after 2007?</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  It is not clear how grants cause teenage pregnancies in rural areas in South Africa.
                </td>
                <td>How do grants cause teenage pregnancies in rural areas in South Africa?</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          This is probably the simplest step, and it may seem too simple, but I put it here because novice
          researchers often make the mistake of creating a question that does not follow from the knowledge problem.
          What this step shows is that the research question is directly derived from the knowledge problem&mdash;that
          it is in fact a mere restatement.
        </p>
        <p>
          Most authors of journal articles and books today don&rsquo;t state their research question, but I advise
          against this for novice researchers. I advise that you state your question explicitly. Questions are active,
          they pull you forward and focus your mind. If you wish, you can restate the question as an aim, but first you
          need a question.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since the aim of research is to answer unanswered questions, the aim of any study is simply a restatement of
          its question, as the next table shows.
        </p>

        <div class="mustdos-table-wrap">
          <table class="mustdos-table">
            <caption class="mustdos-table-caption">
              From research question to aim
            </caption>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th scope="col">Research question</th>
                <th scope="col">The aim of this study is to investigate&hellip;</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>What is 1+1?</td>
                <td>&hellip;what is 1+1.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Will it rain later?</td>
                <td>&hellip;whether it will rain later.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Is the road congested?</td>
                <td>&hellip;whether the road is congested.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Did lower taxes stimulate Colombian consumers to spend after 2007?</td>
                <td>&hellip;if lower taxes stimulated Colombian consumer spending after 2007.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>How do grants cause teenage pregnancies in rural areas in South Africa?</td>
                <td>&hellip;how grants cause teenage pregnancies in rural areas in South Africa.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          Some researchers state their objectives or sub-questions. Objectives are the result of breaking the aim into
          smaller tasks&mdash;that means if you achieved every one of the objectives you would have comprehensively
          achieved the aim. If instead you prefer having a question, you would similarly break the question into smaller
          sub-questions. So you will either have an aim with objectives, or a question with sub-questions.
        </p>
        <p>
          In some studies you need to state a hypothesis. Again the hypothesis is derived from the question, so you need
          to have a question first. An hypothesis is a statement that a research will show to be either true or false.
          It is only meaningful if it could be an answer to your question, and if your research will be able to establish
          whether it is true or false. For example, if my question is &ldquo;what is the colour of the sky?&rdquo; my
          hypothesis could then be &ldquo;the sky is green&rdquo;. That is a statement, and my research can prove that it
          is false. A word of caution: hypotheses are only suitable to questions with unambiguous answers or questions
          where the possible range of answers are known in advance, such as &ldquo;what&hellip;?&rdquo;,
          &ldquo;who&hellip;?&rdquo; or &ldquo;where&hellip;?&rdquo; questions. It is very difficult to develop
          hypotheses for more open-ended questions, like &ldquo;how&hellip;?&rdquo; or &ldquo;why&hellip;?&rdquo;
          questions, so in such cases it is better to simply state the question or the aim.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you think this step seems too simple to be true, you are partly right. At this point you still have only a
          provisional question and you will refine it in the next step. Very often you will find that the next step
          might show weaknesses in your proposed research that will force you to go back to step five, or even back to
          step two.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-7" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #7: Refine the research question</h2>
        <p>
          I will take some liberty with a well-known English saying by stating that &ldquo;the road to a good question
          is paved with stupid questions&rdquo;. Your provisional question is probably a stupid question, but that is
          all right. If you are afraid to begin with a stupid question, you will not end up with a meaningful question.
        </p>
        <p>
          How do you know if a question is stupid or not? A stupid question is meaningless&mdash;it does not make sense
          or is too vague to be answered by research. A question that is not stupid is meaningful since it can be
          answered. A research question is meaningful if it gives very specific guidance on finding the answer. This
          means a question has to meet four conditions in order to be meaningful:
        </p>

        <h3 id="meaningful-conditions">Four conditions for a meaningful question</h3>
        <ul class="mustdos-list">
          <li>A meaningful question makes plausible assumptions;</li>
          <li>A meaningful question tells you what information you need to answer the question;</li>
          <li>A meaningful question tells you where and when you may get the information; and</li>
          <li>A meaningful question tells you by what methods you will get this information.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          The first condition ensures that an answer is possible, while the last three conditions ensure that the
          question is specific enough to be answered. If your question meets the last three conditions you will already
          be halfway to the answer, because you can already tell a lot about the answer from a meaningful question.
        </p>

        <aside class="mustdos-aside">
          <p class="mustdos-aside-title">A meaningful question already gives you the silhouette of the answer</p>
          <p>
            It enables you to see what the answer may look like and what you need to do to find it, even if you
            can&rsquo;t see the details yet. Like a silhouette, you can tell a lot from it even if you can&rsquo;t see
            the details. You can see it is a man and a woman. The woman has long hair, the man has short hair, they are
            probably standing, the woman seems to be angry and scolding the man, and a few more things.
          </p>
        </aside>

        <p>
          How do you make your question meaningful? You simply take every term in the question and define it until it is
          unambiguous. Let&rsquo;s do an example with a meaningless question such as: &ldquo;what is the secret to
          success?&rdquo; There is no way this question can be researched, because it is much too vague. It is not clear
          at all what is meant by &lsquo;success&rsquo;. If we don&rsquo;t know that, then we won&rsquo;t know what
          information is needed, and if we don&rsquo;t know what information we need, we won&rsquo;t know where, when or
          by what method we can get this information. So we have to go through a process of clarifying the question so
          that it becomes researchable&mdash;some people call it &lsquo;operationalising&rsquo; the question.
        </p>

        <h3 id="operationalising">Operationalising the question</h3>
        <p>
          Here is an example of how a question is operationalized, shown as a possible dialogue between a professor and
          a student:
        </p>

        <div class="mustdos-dialogue" aria-label="Professor and student dialogue on operationalising a question">
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> What is your research question?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> It is &lsquo;what is the secret to success?&rsquo;
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> What do you mean by &lsquo;success&rsquo;?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> I mean financial success. So my question is &lsquo;what
            is the secret to financial success?&rsquo;
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> What counts as &lsquo;financial success&rsquo;?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> That is when you have a high net worth. So my question
            is &lsquo;what is the secret to achieving a high net worth?&rsquo;
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> How much is a &lsquo;high&rsquo; net worth?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> High net worth is at least US$10 million. So my question
            is &lsquo;what is the secret to achieving a net worth of US$10 million?&rsquo;
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> Does this apply to any person?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> No, I want to investigate it for Colombians. So my
            question is &lsquo;what is the secret to achieving a net worth of US$10 million in Colombia?&rsquo;
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> Is this for all time or by a certain time?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> No, the person must achieve it before age 50 to be
            financially successful. So my question becomes: &lsquo;what is the secret to achieving a net worth of US$10
            million in Colombia by age 50?&rsquo;
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> What do you mean by &lsquo;secret&rsquo;?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> That would be the method by which to achieve it. So my
            question is &lsquo;by what method can a Colombian achieve a net worth of US$10 million by age 50?&rsquo;
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          This conversation can go on a bit longer as they explore what is meant by &lsquo;achieve&rsquo; (legal or also
          illegal?) or &lsquo;net worth&rsquo; (the kinds of assets and liabilities) or US$10 million (held in US$ or is
          the equivalent in pesos also fine?) or &lsquo;method&rsquo;. But the point is that they came a long way from a
          stupid question like &lsquo;what is the secret to success?&rsquo; to &lsquo;by what method can a Colombian
          achieve a net worth of US$10 million by age 50?&rsquo; which is a more meaningful question that will be much
          easier to research.
        </p>
        <p>
          The above conversation could have gone in many different directions depending on the kind of &lsquo;success&rsquo;
          the student had in mind. There is no correct direction as long as the question meets all four conditions.
          Let&rsquo;s test the question against the four conditions to see if it could work, returning to the dialogue as
          an example:
        </p>

        <h3 id="testing-question">Testing the question</h3>

        <div class="mustdos-dialogue" aria-label="Professor and student dialogue testing the refined question">
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> So your question is &lsquo;by what method can a
            Colombian achieve a net worth of US$10 million by age 50?&rsquo; Let&rsquo;s test it. What information would
            you need to answer the question?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> I would need information on Colombians who have achieved
            this net worth before 50.
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> What else?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> Well the question suggests that I should also find
            information on their net worth and on their life stories to see how they achieved it. I can already see that
            I need to clarify how exactly I will measure net worth, so this means I will have to expand my question a
            little.
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> Where will you get all this information? To get the
            list of people with a high net worth might be tough.
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> Yes, I didn&rsquo;t realise that, so if I can&rsquo;t
            get this I would need to change my question. But for now I would need to find out if there is a list of the
            richest Colombians. I will get their life stories from magazines, newspapers, biographies and talking to
            acquaintances. That is if I can get access to these people and if they would be willing to speak to me.
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> And if not, you would need to adapt your question
            somewhat. Anyway, when, or for what period, will you get this information?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> I can see that the question needs clarification here.
            Because money loses its value over time I should perhaps only focus on people who achieved this net worth in
            the last ten years.
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> By what method, or how exactly, will you obtain all the
            information you need?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> It seems to me that it would involve lots of secondary
            data analysis&mdash;of financial records (if I can find them) and some kind of textual analysis of the life
            stories of the wealthy people. Also, if they are willing to speak to me, I would conduct semi-structured
            interviews with acquaintances, friends or even the successful people themselves.
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> What does your question assume?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> One big assumption of the question is that there are
            methods that one can follow to achieve wealth.
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> Is that a plausible assumption, or is there evidence to
            support it?
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Student:</span> I am not sure; I will have to read some more of the
            literature to see. I can see your point&mdash;if there is no method for achieving wealth, then the question
            cannot be answered, because it assumes that there is a method.
          </p>
          <p class="mustdos-dialogue-turn">
            <span class="mustdos-dialogue-speaker">Professor:</span> So, it seems to me that you made a good start, but it
            is not certain yet if it will be possible to research the question. You still have lots to find out and you
            will probably have to change your question somewhat.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          The best way to test your question is not to check it yourself against the four conditions, because we often
          assume our questions are clearer than they really are. Rather show your question to someone who is familiar
          with your discipline, and ask them: &ldquo;if this were your question, would you know what information you would
          need? Would you know where, when and by what method to get it?&rdquo; If they struggle, or give you answers
          that are not what you expected, it is a sign that you need to clarify your question.
        </p>
        <p>
          As you refine your question, it gets longer and longer, as you saw in the above dialogue. Perhaps the question
          ends up being: &lsquo;what are the ten most common legal methods by which Colombians have achieved a tangible
          net worth of US$10 million (or its equivalent) by age 50 in the last ten years?&rsquo; It may happen that the
          question gets too long and clumsy, and the solution is to add delimitations (note that &lsquo;delimitations&rsquo;
          are very different from &lsquo;limitations&rsquo;). Delimitations are boundaries you place around the question.
        </p>

        <h3 id="delimitations">Delimitations</h3>
        <p>
          What you can do is state the short version of your question, and then add a paragraph underneath it in which you
          explain your question (the delimitations). For example:
        </p>

        <div class="mustdos-example">
          <p>
            The research question of this study is: what are the most common methods by which Colombians have achieved
            financial success before the age of 50?
          </p>
          <p>
            Financial success is defined as having a tangible net worth of more than US$100 million, or the equivalent in
            another currency. Tangible net worth is the value of total assets minus total liabilities and excluding the
            value of intangible assets. The study will focus only on Colombians who have achieved this net worth in the
            last ten years, that is the period 2006&ndash;2015. This study will identify the ten most common methods,
            categorised by kind of industry, by which they achieved their wealth.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          Many students underestimate the importance of refining their questions at this very early stage, and as a
          result they are never able to complete their research because they tried to research a non-researchable
          question. As you may have noticed from the dialogues above, checking your question against the conditions for a
          meaningful question allows you to change and clarify your question before it is too late.
        </p>
        <p>
          Now, and I mean <strong>NOW</strong>, is the time to think about what it will take to answer your question, and
          to determine if you will be able to answer it. From the above dialogue the student realised that he needed
          access to information that might not be possible to obtain, or he might have realised that he doesn&rsquo;t have
          the skill to use the required methods. He might then either have to change his question to make it more
          feasible, or obtain the necessary skills or contacts before proceeding with his question. In my experience too
          many students get stuck in their research later, or have to start all over again, because they never spent much
          time on this step.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-8" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #8: Write the &lsquo;Research problem&rsquo; section</h2>
        <p>
          By now you realise that all scientific research is about meaningful questions that derive from two
          problems&mdash;a real-world problem followed by a knowledge problem. You need both a real-world problem and a
          knowledge problem. To see why:
        </p>

        <ul class="mustdos-list">
          <li>
            Consider the following famous question from the Middle Ages: how many angels can dance on the head of a pin?
            This is a useless research question because even if we knew the answer it would not help to address any
            problem in the real world.
          </li>
          <li>
            Or consider this question: what will happen to sales of fuel when the oil price goes down? While this
            question would help to solve a problem, it is not useful to do research on it because we already know the
            answer from previous research. More research will not contribute anything new to what we know.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          To write the &ldquo;Research problem and question&rdquo; section you need to start where the previous section
          ended&mdash;with the real-world problem. By referring to previous scientific studies, show how inadequate
          scientific knowledge is about the real-world problem. You don&rsquo;t explain anything about the real world
          now, but you explain the knowledge problem about the real-world problem with reference to the important studies
          (step 5), and then derive your research question explicitly (from step 6 and 7). Based on your unpacking the
          terms you add a paragraph or two where you provide the delimitations of the questions (step 7).
        </p>
        <p>Here is an extract from an actual proposal, with the details deleted.</p>

        <div class="mustdos-example">
          <p class="mustdos-example-title">Research problem and question</p>
          <p>
            There are many international studies which discuss the ___. The studies which do analyse ___ have different
            aims to ___. For example, a study by Sapenzia (2002) claimed that ___. This study does assess the impact ___
            however it is focused on ___. Similarly, another study conducted by Petersen and Raghuram (1995) compared
            ___ but ___. While a further study conducted by Drucker (2005) analysed the ___ it only focused narrowly on
            ___ rather than on ___.
          </p>
          <p>
            The South African studies on ___ focus on the factors which ___ the South African economy. These studies have
            ___ (Fedderke &amp; Romm, 2004; Moolman et al., 2006). Unfortunately these studies look only at factors
            influencing ___ and not specifically ___. Other South African studies assess ___ (Affleck-Graves et al.,
            1988; Bhana, 1987; Van Den Honert, 1988). Although these results can possibly be applicable to ___, the
            above mentioned South African studies analyse the impact of ___ on ___ and again not specifically on ___.
          </p>
          <p>
            In summary, international literature on ___ does exist however there is limited ___. Furthermore, although
            there are studies in a South African context that ___, there is no research on ___. Since ___ is unknown,
            the research question follows: ___?
          </p>
          <p>
            The term ___ refers to a ___. The ___ refers to the impact on ____. The desired state would be that ___.
            ___ will be measured by ___.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          Once you have a researchable question, you are ready to think about what you will do to find the answer.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-9" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #9: Think about how you will find the answer</h2>
        <p>
          In this step you write up your provisional research design and methodology section. In this section you tell us,
          in as much detail as possible, how exactly you will conduct your research in order to find the answer.
        </p>
        <p>
          Many students think that it is impossible to explain this so early in the research, but that would be wrong&mdash;you
          can already tell us a lot. You already know what it will take to obtain your results because you thought about
          it in step 7 when you refined your question. If at this stage you cannot write at least two or three paragraphs
          about how you will conduct your research, it is likely that your question is not so meaningful and that you
          should go back to step 7.
        </p>
        <p>
          So, what can you tell us already about your research design? The next table shows this, according to the last
          three conditions of a meaningful question.
        </p>

        <div class="mustdos-table-wrap">
          <table class="mustdos-table">
            <caption class="mustdos-table-caption">
              From meaningful question to provisional research design
            </caption>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th scope="col">A meaningful question tells you&hellip;</th>
                <th scope="col">So you should know and be able to explain&hellip;</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>&hellip;what information you will need</td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="mustdos-table-list">
                    <li>Which variables to investigate</li>
                    <li>What data is needed on each one</li>
                    <li>Whether this data is available</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>&hellip;where and when to get this information</td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="mustdos-table-list">
                    <li>The sources of each individual variable</li>
                    <li>For what period and place the data will be gathered</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>&hellip;by what method you will obtain the information</td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="mustdos-table-list">
                    <li>How exactly you will obtain the data</li>
                    <li>How you will analyse the data</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          In the provisional research design and methodology section you need to convince the reader that you know
          exactly what needs to be done to answer the question. The things you need to explain here are exactly the
          things you had to think about when refining your question: variables, data sources, time period, data gathering
          methods and techniques of data analysis. &lsquo;Data&rsquo; refers to any credible quantitative or qualitative
          information that you can use to help you answer the question.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you are vague at this point it harms your credibility, because it creates the impression that you
          don&rsquo;t know what you are doing. Vagueness is also a sign that your question is not researchable, and that
          you are trying to hide this.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="must-do-10" class="mustdos-section">
        <h2>Must do #10: Tell us why the research is significant</h2>
        <p>
          In this final step, we close the circle and write the &lsquo;Significance of the research&rsquo; section. You
          go back to the real world, and you ask yourself: who will benefit from this research? Now you need not limit
          yourself only to those with the power to solve the problem; you can include everyone with an interest in the
          problem. Tell us how they would gain once the research is completed. How would your research make a positive
          difference to their lives in the real world?
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="summary" class="mustdos-section mustdos-section--summary">
        <h2>Summary</h2>
        <p>
          Let&rsquo;s summarise the process. Research starts with something personal&mdash;an issue or problem that you
          care about and want to find out more about (#1). You have to make other people care about it, specifically
          those with the power to take action, by showing that there is a problem for them in the real world about which
          something needs to be done (#2 to #4). Then you look at the research about this real-world problem, and show
          that previous studies are inadequate, and as a result we have a knowledge problem (#5).
        </p>

        <figure class="mustdos-figure mustdos-figure--wide">
          <img
            src={imgRealWorldKnowledge}
            alt="Cartoon contrast: practitioners asking what is wrong with our reality versus books asking why we are inadequate."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>
            Real-world problem (left): what is wrong with our reality? Knowledge problem (right): why are the studies
            inadequate?
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The real-world problem and the scientific (i.e. knowledge) problem are often confused by novice researchers. So
          look at the pictures above. For yourself you write about the facts that relate to the experience of people
          trying to solve a real-world problem. In the assignment you don&rsquo;t write about the real world as such,
          but rather about the studies done in the past and where they are missing something. This is summarised in
          another way in the table below:
        </p>

        <h3 id="two-problems">Real-world vs knowledge problem</h3>

        <div class="mustdos-table-wrap">
          <table class="mustdos-table">
            <caption class="mustdos-table-caption">Comparing the two kinds of problem</caption>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th scope="col"></th>
                <th scope="col">Real-world problem</th>
                <th scope="col">Knowledge problem</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Where is the problem?</th>
                <td>In the everyday reality of people and things</td>
                <td>In the studies on the real-world problem</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Who experiences it?</th>
                <td>People: practitioners and those with the power to address the problem</td>
                <td>Scholars with an interest in the research</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">How do we prove it?</th>
                <td>Provide facts in support of the seriousness of the problem</td>
                <td>Evidence that research to date is inadequate</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>If you can summarise the background section in the following three sentences, you are ready to write it up:</p>

        <div class="mustdos-example">
          <p>
            The problem in reality for ________ is ________. The main facts that suggest that there is a problem are
            ________. This group should pay attention to it because ________.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>If you can summarise the knowledge problem in the following three sentences, you are ready to write it up:</p>

        <div class="mustdos-example">
          <p>
            The studies about [the real-world problem] are inadequate because ________. We therefore do not know
            ________. So the question is: ________?
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          Once you rephrase the knowledge problem as a question (#6) you refine your question by testing it against the
          conditions for a meaningful question (#7), and you write up the &lsquo;Research problem&rsquo; section (#8). If
          you did a good job at refining your question you should have a lot of clarity on how you will conduct the
          research (#9). Finally, you close the circle and return to the real world in step 10.
        </p>

        <h3 id="proposal-template">Proposal template</h3>
        <p>Below is a possible template for a research proposal based on the steps discussed in this reading.</p>

        <ol class="mustdos-template">
          <li>
            <strong>Introduction to the research</strong> (more or less 1 page)
            <p>
              Argue that there is a problem (the problem would have originated in the real world but you have managed to
              translate it into scientific terms) within the scientific discourse within a discipline or research field.
              Identify the relevant group that will be interested in this research and use facts from credible sources to
              support your case that there is a problem that this group should take seriously, and why.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Literature that supports the argument</strong> (about 15 pages)
            <p>
              Now go to the literature and explain what aspect of this problem has not been researched adequately. Use
              literature to give evidence and support the argument made in section one.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Research problem and question</strong> (about &frac12; page)
            <p>
              Clearly identify the gap in the research by a brief but systematic overview of the literature. Convert it
              into a question.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Research design</strong> (about 1 page)
            <p>
              What will it take to answer this question? What needs to be done and is it feasible? What data do you
              need/create and is this feasible? Did you check? Where will you get this data from? Is it accessible? Did
              you check? Provide some details of what will go into your model, survey, or whatever design you will use.
              Did previous studies also use this approach or do you need to adapt it? How? Did you check this is
              feasible? What are these studies?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>List of references</strong> (30 or so references are fine at this stage)
            <p>
              Sections 1, 2 and 3 should contain lots of references. Provide their details here in the correct format.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          Research is a journey that only makes sense when you reach the end. There will be many tough times, you will
          find yourself repeatedly backing out of blind alleys and letting go of leads that have disappointed once again,
          but your passion will pull you through these times. It is only those who expect research to be difficult who
          will be able to manage it, and you should now have a good foundation and sufficient excitement to pull you
          through.
        </p>
        <p>
          Feeling overwhelmed, dejected and lost is an important part of this journey, because this is no ordinary
          journey. You are not simply going to a known destination that is well-known; you are not merely discovering
          things that others know; you are discovering things that nobody knows. It is a journey of creation, and you
          don&rsquo;t simply reach the endpoint, you create it. And once you are at the endpoint, you will realise that it
          is not the end after all, simply the beginning of new journeys, for yourself or others.
        </p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

